itary\n**The Pelican 1090 HardBack case is introduced\n*'''2010'''\n**Pelican's Chairman of the Board, Peter Pace initiates the Pelican For Patriots program which provides cases for wounded military veterans to protect their prosthetic\n**Pelican sends coolers, flashlights and cases to aid in the Haiti disaster rescue and recovery\n**Pelican introduces Advanced Case Solutions line for custom case applications\n**Pelican is certified as a Sony Green Partner\n**Pelican introduces the 1460 EMS case for the emergency and fire safety markets\n*'''2011'''\n**Pelican purchased Australian roto-mold case manufacturer Trimcast <ref>[http://www.healthcarepackaging.com/trends-and-issues/cold-chain/pelican-acquires-minnesota-thermal-science Pelican Acquires Trimcast], www.growthbusiness.co.uk, 2011-04-05, Retrieved 2013-09-20.</ref>\n**Pelican India and South Korea open\n**Pelican wins the National Institute of Packaging Handling and Logistics Engineers (NIPHLE) 2011 Corporation of the Year award\n**Pelican receives the Presidential \"E\" award for exports\n*'''2013'''\n** The company introduces their consumer division, offering backpacks, lighting tools, coolers and more<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/16/business/media/pelican-products-maneuvers-to-add-customers-without-losing-any-advertising.html?_r=0 A Product With Devotees Tries to Widen Its Niche], www.nytimes.com, 2012-08-05, Retrieved 2013-09-20.</ref>\n** The company acquired temperature-controlled container manufacturer Minnesota Thermal Science <ref>[http://www.healthcarepackaging.com/trends-and-issues/cold-chain/pelican-acquires-minnesota-thermal-science Pelican acquires Minnesota Thermal Science], www.healthcarepackaging.com, 01-14-2013, Retrieved 2013-09-20</ref>\n*'''2014 - 20015'''\n** Pelican introduces the Pelican 7000 flashlight, their first to shine up to 600 lumens\n** Pelican introduces Pelican Elite luggage\n** Pelican acquires Cool Logistics and re-brands the combined division (Minnesota Thermal Science + Cool Logistics) as Pelican BioThermal<ref name=\"healthcarepackaging.com\">{{Cite web|url = http://www.healthcarepackaging.com/pelican-products-inc-accelerates-its-biopharma-strategy-acquisition-cool-logistics|title = Pelican Products, Inc. accelerates its BioPharma strategy with the acquisition of Cool Logistics|date = 2014-02-04|accessdate = 2015-10-06|website = www.heathcarepackaging.com|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n*'''2016 - 2017'''\n** Pelican celebrates its 40th anniversary\n**Pelican introduces their Pelican Air Case line\n**Pelican introduces Pelican Traveler tumblers\n** Peli BioThermal wins the Queen's Award for Innovation\n*'''2018 - 2019'''\n** Peli BioThermal wins the Queen's Award for Enterprise\n**Pelican introduces the \"Vault by Pelican\" line as a brand extension to its case line\n**Pelican launches its first e-commerce site at [[www.pelican.com/shop]]\n*'''2020'''\n**Pelican acquires NanoCool, a temperature-controlled packaging manufacturer.\n\n==Cases==\n[[Image:Pelican Products iPod Case.jpg|thumb|right|A water-resistant Pelican Products iPod case]]\nPelican cases are molded plastic containers that seal with an airtight and watertight gasket. Pelican cases include a barometric relief valve made of [[Gore-Tex]] to prevent pressure damage to the case during transportation or when the air pressure in the environment changes. Pelican cases meet standards for waterproofing, stacking, impact, and durability including [[MIL-STD]] C4150-J for waterproofing, [[International Electrotechnical Commission|IEC]] [[IP Code|IP67]] rating indicating complete sealing against dust and water immersion to 1 metre, as well as [[ATA 300]] rating indicating compliance with [[Air Transport Association]] standards for durability in shipping. Pelican cases feature a lifetime guarantee. In Europe, they are sold as Peli cases.\n\nIf the case falls into water, generally there will be enough air in the case to keep it afloat. The barometric relief valve permits air to pass through, but not water or other liquids. Under some extreme conditions leakage is technically possible, but such conditions are unlikely to be encountered, except in the case of deliberate vandalism.\n\nPelican Products also manufactures customized rotationally molded cases built for specialized sensitive equipment protection. The cases can be modified with features including internal shock-mount systems, manual pressure relief valves, humidity indicators, custom foam, and fabricated metal framing for electronics. Pelican Products also runs a series of Advanced Case Centers in California, Virginia, Massachusetts, Canada, France, United Kingdom, and Australia that handle customization and design work for their cases.{{cn|date=November 2018}} The official distributor in Russia is Protect Studio.<ref>Official distributor in Russia https://protect.studio/about/</ref>\n\n== Temperature Controlled Packaging ==\nPelican's BioThermal division offers passive temperature-controlled products and service solutions including single-use and reusable parcels, single use and reusable pallets and rental programs for the pharmaceutical industry.\n\n==Flashlights==\nPelican flashlights (known as ''Pelican Lights'') use [[Incandescent light bulb|Xenon]], [[Halogen lamp|Halogen]], and [[LED]] lamps. Many are safety approved with features such as valves, anti-shock systems, and battery polarity guards. The safety approvals<ref name=\"safety\">{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.ul.com/global/eng/pages/offerings/services/hazardouslocations/techsummary/\n |title       = Technical Summary - Classified Locations\n |work        = www.ul.com\n |publisher   = [[Underwriter Laboratories]]\n |accessdate  = 2013-09-16\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20130905033621/http://www.ul.com/global/eng/pages/offerings/services/hazardouslocations/techsummary/\n |archivedate = 2013-09-05\n}}</ref> include ETL ([[ETL SEMKO|Edison Testing Labs]]), UL ([[Underwriters Laboratories]]), FM ([[Factory Mutual]]), CE-EX ([[ATEX directive|ATEX Europe]]), CSA ([[Canadian Standards Association]]), MSHA ([[Mine Safety and Health Administration]])<ref name=\"msha-safety\">{{cite web\n      | url = http://www.msha.gov/TECHSUPP/ACC/lists/20flshlt.pdf\n      | title = List of Approved Products\n      | work = www.msha.gov\n      | date = September 2001\n      | accessdate = 2013-09-16\n    }}</ref> and the AUS (Australian Board of Approvals). The company also manufactures a line of LED tactical flashlights geared toward the law enforcement community.\n\n== Travel Goods and Drinkware ==\nPelican manufactures a line of backpacks, duffel bags, travel-themed cases, double-walled tumblers and bottles aimed toward travelers.\n\n==Remote area lighting==\nPelican's Advanced Area Lighting Group (AALG) designs and manufactures a variety of battery powered, remote area lighting solutions (RALS). These range from single head, hand held units to deployable units with up to four separate LED heads, as well as tent lighting. Rapid setup and long run times for emergency responders, military, maintenance workers, and others.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Maglite]]\n*[[Flashlight]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Flashlights]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "Performed minor cleanup.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pelican_Products"}
{"title_page": "Kapyl", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type    = Town\n|name = Kapyl / Kopyl\n|native_name = \u041a\u0430\u043f\u044b\u043b\u044c / \u041a\u043e\u043f\u044b\u043b\u044c \n|image_skyline = Kapyl.jpg\n|imagesize = 250px\n|image_flag = Flag of Kapyl.svg\n|image_shield = Coat of Arms of Kapyl, Belarus.svg\n|pushpin_map = Belarus\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location in Belarus\n|subdivision_type   = Country\n|subdivision_name   = {{flag|Belarus}}\n|subdivision_type1=Region\n|subdivision_name1=[[File:Flag of minsk province.svg|20px|border]] [[Minsk Region]]\n|subdivision_type2=District\n|subdivision_name2=[[Kapyl District]]\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|established_title = First mentioned\n|established_date = 1274\n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_water_km2 = \n|population_as_of = 2009\n|population_note = \n|population_total = 9,900\n|population_metro = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset = +2\n|timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST = +3\n|coordinates      = {{coord|53|09|0|N|27|05|30|E|region:BY|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m = \n|postal_code = 223 910, 223 927\n|area_code = +375 1719\n|blank_name = \n|blank_info = \n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Kapyl''' ({{lang-be|\u041a\u0430\u043f\u044b\u0301\u043b\u044c|Kapy\u013a}}, {{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u043f\u044b\u043b\u044c|Kopyl}}; {{lang-pl|Kopyl}}; {{lang-lt|Kapylius}}; {{lang-yi|\u05e7\u05d0\u05e4\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05e2}}) is an urban settlement and the capital of [[Kapyl District]] in [[Belarus]].  It is located {{convert|34|km|mi|sp=us}} west-northwest of [[Slutsk]] and {{convert|90|km|mi|sp=us}} south-southwest of [[Minsk]].<ref name=\"Kapyl, Belarus on JewishGen.Org\">[http://data.jewishgen.org/wconnect/wc.dll?jg~jgsys~shtetm~-1944511], Kapyl, Belarus on JewishGen.Org accessed 13 July 2010</ref> The current population estimate of 9,900 for the town is based on the provisional figures from the 2009 census.<ref name=\"Belarus City Population\">[http://www.citypopulation.de/Belarus.html], Belarus City Population accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\nThe postal codes for Kapyl are 223910 and 223927.<ref name=\"Kopyl raion page at Minks Oblispolkom\">[http://www.minsk-region.gov.by/index.aspx?id=23] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227191533/http://www.minsk-region.gov.by/index.aspx?id=23 |date=2012-02-27 }} Kopyl raion page at Minsk [[Oblispolkom]] website accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nKapyl, first mentioned in 1274,<ref name=\"Kopyl Region Executive Committee\">[https://archive.today/20121204010244/http://www.kopyl.minsk-region.by/en/region/town/history], Kopyl Region Executive Committee website retrieved 20 July 2010</ref> was a walled town that was noteworthy by the 14th century, and is listed in the atlas of [[Ortelius]] of 1574.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\"/> During the 14th century the town was part of the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]]. In 1395 it came into the possession of Prince [[Vladimir Olgerdovich]] and his heirs, the [[Olelkovich]] family, where it remained until 1612.  Kapyl was part of the dowry of [[Sophia Olelkovich Radziwill|Zofia Olelkowicz S\u0142ucka]] and was one of the seven fortified towns left to her husband [[Janusz Radziwill (1579\u20131620)|Janusz Radziwill]] upon her death in 1612.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\">[http://dir.icm.edu.pl/pl/Slownik_geograficzny/Tom_IV/386], Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom and other Slavic countries (in Polish), vol 4, edited by F. Sulimirskiego, B. Chlebowski, W. Walewski, Warsaw 1883, pp. 386-387 accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\nKapyl was attacked by the [[Tatars]] numerous times and was sacked on at least one occasion during the 16th century.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\"/>\n\nOn August 27, 1652, Kapyl received the [[Magdeburg Law]] and gained its own seal, a coat of arms depicting a hunting horn on a gold field.  With this privilege came the right to hold fairs and weekly auctions.  During the 16th century weaving became established in the town, including the production of velvet.  Six guilds came into existence as a result of the growth of the weaving industry.\n\nAfter the [[Second Partition of Poland]] in 1793 Kapyl became part of the [[Russian Empire]].  From 1832 it became a personal holding of [[Peter Wittgenstein|Prince Wittgenstein]].  During the 19th century local businesses included a brewery, 2 water mills, and 6 shops.   Other local institutions included 3 schools, churches (including a [[Calvinist]] church), and 2 Jewish [[synagogue]]s.\n\nTowards the end of the 19th century Kapyl had over 350 houses and over 2000 inhabitants.  At that time a majority of the town\u2019s population was Jewish.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\"/>  By 1900 the Jewish population was 2,671.<ref name=\"Kapyl, Belarus on JewishGen.Org\"/>\n\nIn 1924, Kapyl became the capital city of the Kapyl District.\n\nDuring [[World War II]] the Slutsk-Kapyl area was the subject of a German military operation code-named Erntefest II (Harvest Festival) which ended in February 1943.  Although ostensibly aimed at suppressing the activities of Soviet partisans in the area the operation resulted in the deaths of 2,325 of the local inhabitants (against the loss of six German soldiers), which can only be characterized as a campaign of genocide and terror.<ref name=\"Rodoh Forum: Major Antipartisan Operations in Belorussia\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20101025103351/http://rodohforum.yuku.com/topic/2482], Rodoh Forum: Major Antipartisan Operations in Belorussia accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\nOne of Kapyl district\u2019s major architectural monuments is a 19th-century church in the town itself.<ref name=\"Kapyl District at Treklens\">[http://www.treklens.com/gallery/photo448602.htm], Kapyl District at Treklens accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\n==Personalities==\nKapyl is also known as the birthplace of [[Mendele Mocher Sforim]].\n\n==Sister cities==\n*{{flagicon|LIT}} [[Joni\u0161kis]], Lithuania<ref>{{cite web|title=International Relations|url=http://www.joniskis.lt/International%20relations%20713|work=joniskis.lt|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[List of towns with German town law]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [http://dir.icm.edu.pl/pl/Slownik_geograficzny/Tom_IV/386 Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom and other Slavic countries (in Polish), vol 4, edited by F. Sulimirskiego, B. Chlebowski, W. Walewski, Warsaw 1883, pp 386-387.]\n\n==External links==\n* {{JewishGen-LocalityPage|1944511|Kapyl, Belarus}}\n* [http://www.treklens.com/gallery/photo448602.htm Kapyl District at Treklens]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120227191533/http://www.minsk-region.gov.by/index.aspx?id=23 Kopyl raion page at Minsk [[Oblispolkom]] website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101025103351/http://rodohforum.yuku.com/topic/2482 Rodoh Forum: Major Antipartisan Operations in Belorussia]\n* [https://archive.today/20121204010244/http://www.kopyl.minsk-region.by/en/region/town/history Kopyl Region Executive Committee]\n* [http://www.citypopulation.de/Belarus.html Belarus City Population]\n\n{{Minsk Voblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Minsk Region]]\n[[Category:Kapyl District]]\n[[Category:Towns in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Nowogr\u00f3dek Voivodeship (1507\u20131795)]]\n[[Category:Slutsky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Belarus]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type    = Town\n|name = Kapyl / Kopyl\n|native_name = \u041a\u0430\u043f\u044b\u043b\u044c / \u041a\u043e\u043f\u044b\u043b\u044c \n|image_skyline = Kapyl.jpg\n|imagesize = 250px\n|image_flag = Flag of Kapyl.svg\n|image_shield = Coat of Arms of Kapyl, Belarus.svg\n|pushpin_map = Belarus\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location in Belarus\n|subdivision_type   = Country\n|subdivision_name   = {{flag|Belarus}}\n|subdivision_type1=Region\n|subdivision_name1=[[File:Flag of minsk province.svg|20px|border]] [[Minsk Region]]\n|subdivision_type2=District\n|subdivision_name2=[[Kapyl District]]\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|established_title = First mentioned\n|established_date = 1274\n|area_magnitude = \n|area_total_km2 = \n|area_land_km2 = \n|area_water_km2 = \n|population_as_of = 2009\n|population_note = \n|population_total = 9,900\n|population_metro = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset = +2\n|timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST = +3\n|coordinates      = {{coord|53|09|0|N|27|05|30|E|region:BY|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m = \n|postal_code = 223 910, 223 927\n|area_code = +375 1719\n|blank_name = \n|blank_info = \n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\n'''Kapyl''' ({{lang-be|\u041a\u0430\u043f\u044b\u0301\u043b\u044c|Kopy\u013a}}, {{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u043f\u044b\u043b\u044c|Kopyl}}; {{lang-pl|Kopyl}}; {{lang-lt|Kapylius}}; {{lang-yi|\u05e7\u05d0\u05e4\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9\u05e2}}) is an urban settlement and the capital of [[Kapyl District]] in [[Belarus]].  It is located {{convert|34|km|mi|sp=us}} west-northwest of [[Slutsk]] and {{convert|90|km|mi|sp=us}} south-southwest of [[Minsk]].<ref name=\"Kapyl, Belarus on JewishGen.Org\">[http://data.jewishgen.org/wconnect/wc.dll?jg~jgsys~shtetm~-1944511], Kapyl, Belarus on JewishGen.Org accessed 13 July 2010</ref> The current population estimate of 9,900 for the town is based on the provisional figures from the 2009 census.<ref name=\"Belarus City Population\">[http://www.citypopulation.de/Belarus.html], Belarus City Population accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\nThe postal codes for Kapyl are 223910 and 223927.<ref name=\"Kopyl raion page at Minks Oblispolkom\">[http://www.minsk-region.gov.by/index.aspx?id=23] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227191533/http://www.minsk-region.gov.by/index.aspx?id=23 |date=2012-02-27 }} Kopyl raion page at Minsk [[Oblispolkom]] website accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nKapyl, first mentioned in 1274,<ref name=\"Kopyl Region Executive Committee\">[https://archive.today/20121204010244/http://www.kopyl.minsk-region.by/en/region/town/history], Kopyl Region Executive Committee website retrieved 20 July 2010</ref> was a walled town that was noteworthy by the 14th century, and is listed in the atlas of [[Ortelius]] of 1574.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\"/> During the 14th century the town was part of the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]]. In 1395 it came into the possession of Prince [[Vladimir Olgerdovich]] and his heirs, the [[Olelkovich]] family, where it remained until 1612.  Kapyl was part of the dowry of [[Sophia Olelkovich Radziwill|Zofia Olelkowicz S\u0142ucka]] and was one of the seven fortified towns left to her husband [[Janusz Radziwill (1579\u20131620)|Janusz Radziwill]] upon her death in 1612.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\">[http://dir.icm.edu.pl/pl/Slownik_geograficzny/Tom_IV/386], Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom and other Slavic countries (in Polish), vol 4, edited by F. Sulimirskiego, B. Chlebowski, W. Walewski, Warsaw 1883, pp. 386-387 accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\nKapyl was attacked by the [[Tatars]] numerous times and was sacked on at least one occasion during the 16th century.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\"/>\n\nOn August 27, 1652, Kapyl received the [[Magdeburg Law]] and gained its own seal, a coat of arms depicting a hunting horn on a gold field.  With this privilege came the right to hold fairs and weekly auctions.  During the 16th century weaving became established in the town, including the production of velvet.  Six guilds came into existence as a result of the growth of the weaving industry.\n\nAfter the [[Second Partition of Poland]] in 1793 Kapyl became part of the [[Russian Empire]].  From 1832 it became a personal holding of [[Peter Wittgenstein|Prince Wittgenstein]].  During the 19th century local businesses included a brewery, 2 water mills, and 6 shops.   Other local institutions included 3 schools, churches (including a [[Calvinist]] church), and 2 Jewish [[synagogue]]s.\n\nTowards the end of the 19th century Kapyl had over 350 houses and over 2000 inhabitants.  At that time a majority of the town\u2019s population was Jewish.<ref name=\"Geographical Dictionary of Polish Kingdom\"/>  By 1900 the Jewish population was 2,671.<ref name=\"Kapyl, Belarus on JewishGen.Org\"/>\n\nIn 1924, Kapyl became the capital city of the Kapyl District.\n\nDuring [[World War II]] the Slutsk-Kapyl area was the subject of a German military operation code-named Erntefest II (Harvest Festival) which ended in February 1943.  Although ostensibly aimed at suppressing the activities of Soviet partisans in the area the operation resulted in the deaths of 2,325 of the local inhabitants (against the loss of six German soldiers), which can only be characterized as a campaign of genocide and terror.<ref name=\"Rodoh Forum: Major Antipartisan Operations in Belorussia\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20101025103351/http://rodohforum.yuku.com/topic/2482], Rodoh Forum: Major Antipartisan Operations in Belorussia accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\nOne of Kapyl district\u2019s major architectural monuments is a 19th-century church in the town itself.<ref name=\"Kapyl District at Treklens\">[http://www.treklens.com/gallery/photo448602.htm], Kapyl District at Treklens accessed 13 July 2010</ref>\n\n==Personalities==\nKapyl is also known as the birthplace of [[Mendele Mocher Sforim]].\n\n==Sister cities==\n*{{flagicon|LIT}} [[Joni\u0161kis]], Lithuania<ref>{{cite web|title=International Relations|url=http://www.joniskis.lt/International%20relations%20713|work=joniskis.lt|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[List of towns with German town law]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further read